38. Syri, Macae, aut Dionysi] These were common names of slaves. The practice of executin criminals by throwing them from the Tarpeian Roek (part of the Mons gapitolinus) was not common in the latter period of the republic. It was never applied to slaves, who were put to death, chiefly by crucifixion, outside the city on the Esquilias. (See Epod. v. 99, n). Cadmus is said to have been a public executione-r of that day.
